# Modern Essentials — Windsurf Rules
# Read this before every response. This is the law.

## Project
Subscription-first D2C fresh essentials brand. Reference doc: modern_essentials_blueprint_v2.md (in workspace root).

## Stack — never deviate
- Monorepo: Turborepo + pnpm workspaces
- Frontend: Next.js 14 App Router + TypeScript strict + Tailwind + shadcn/ui
- Backend: NestJS + TypeScript strict + class-validator + Swagger
- ORM: Prisma (never TypeORM, never raw SQL unless migration)
- DB: PostgreSQL
- Queue: BullMQ on Upstash Redis
- Auth: Clerk
- Payments: Razorpay Subscriptions API
- Package manager: pnpm ONLY (never npm or yarn)

## Coding rules
- TypeScript strict mode everywhere. No `any`. No type assertions without comment.
- Every NestJS module gets: module.ts, controller.ts, service.ts, dto.ts
- Every Prisma query that picks inventory MUST ORDER BY expires_at ASC (FEFO law)
- Every Razorpay webhook handler MUST check webhook_events table for idempotency first
- Rewards balance is NEVER updated directly. Append to ledger_entries only.
- Subscription status transitions happen ONLY in the subscription service, never in controllers
- No console.log in committed code. Use NestJS Logger.
- All environment variables must exist in .env.example with a description comment

## Structure
- apps/web — Next.js storefront
- apps/api — NestJS backend
- apps/admin — Next.js ops dashboard
- packages/db — Prisma schema + migrations
- packages/types — shared interfaces + Zod schemas
- packages/utils — shared helpers
- packages/email — React Email templates
- packages/config — ESLint, Prettier, TS configs

## Phase discipline
We build phase by phase. Currently: Phase 1, Week 1.
Never build ahead of the current week without explicit instruction.
When a week is complete, say "Week N complete. Ready for Week N+1 when you are."

## Before writing any code
1. State what you are about to build in one sentence
2. List files you will create or modify
3. Ask if there are any questions
4. Then write the code